support PNG, JPEG, and SVG.

00:01:32.165 --> 00:01:34.550
So what's the difference
between these formats?

00:01:34.550 --> 00:01:37.325
Well, let's start
with JPEG or JPEG.

00:01:37.325 --> 00:01:39.980
Jpeg is one of the
most popular formats

00:01:39.980 --> 00:01:41.720
that you can use
for your images.

00:01:41.720 --> 00:01:44.030
It has a very good
level of compression.

00:01:44.030 --> 00:01:46.190
Therefore, your image sizes will

00:01:46.190 --> 00:01:48.575
be smaller if you use JPEG,

00:01:48.575 --> 00:01:50.720
however, the trade-off
is you don't

00:01:50.720 --> 00:01:53.420
get transparent background
when you use JPEG.

00:01:53.420 --> 00:01:56.960
So in this case, since we
have rounded corners here

00:01:56.960 --> 00:01:58.325
and we need to get

00:01:58.325 --> 00:02:00.860
transparent backgrounds
for these cards.

00:02:00.860 --> 00:02:03.140
We can use JPEG, instead.

00:02:03.140 --> 00:02:04.685
We need to use PNG.

00:02:04.685 --> 00:02:07.580
Png is another popular
format that you can use for

00:02:07.580 --> 00:02:10.460
your images and it lets
you export your assets.

00:02:10.460 --> 00:02:12.005
We transparent backgrounds.

00:02:12.005 --> 00:02:13.130
Therefore, we can create

00:02:13.130 --> 00:02:16.040
some overlaying graphics
and it's so useful.

00:02:16.040 --> 00:02:17.915
But what about SVG?

00:02:17.915 --> 00:02:20.614
Svg is a vector file format.

00:02:20.614 --> 00:02:23.540
So if you create a
simple shape, e.g.

00:02:23.540 --> 00:02:26.570
if you create a circle,
let me show you.

00:02:26.570 --> 00:02:27.695
Just like that.

00:02:27.695 --> 00:02:30.470
You can export it
using the SVG format.

00:02:30.470 --> 00:02:33.980
So what's the difference
when you use the SVG format?

00:02:33.980 --> 00:02:36.500
This file will be
scalable without

00:02:36.500 --> 00:02:39.350
losing quality because
it's a vector file.

00:02:39.350 --> 00:02:41.315
But when we export an image,

00:02:41.315 --> 00:02:42.995
it will be a raster file,

00:02:42.995 --> 00:02:44.465
and when we scale it,

00:02:44.465 --> 00:02:45.965
it will lose quality.

00:02:45.965 --> 00:02:49.895
So whenever it's possible to
export your files using SVG,

00:02:49.895 --> 00:02:51.170
make sure to do that.

00:02:51.170 --> 00:02:54.305
However, it's only
possible for vector files.

00:02:54.305 --> 00:02:56.210
For instance, when you create

00:02:56.210 --> 00:02:58.400
a logo and your logo
is a vector file,

00:02:58.400 --> 00:03:00.755
make sure to export
it using SVG.

00:03:00.755 --> 00:03:02.105
But for these images,

00:03:02.105 --> 00:03:04.160
it's not possible to use SVG

00:03:04.160 --> 00:03:06.320
because these are
not vector files,

00:03:06.320 --> 00:03:07.835
these are raster files.

00:03:07.835 --> 00:03:09.425
So I'm going to
remove this circle.

00:03:09.425 --> 00:03:13.595
So SVG format provides you
with small file sizes,

00:03:13.595 --> 00:03:15.350
then J peg provides you with

00:03:15.350 --> 00:03:18.575
the smallest file
size, and finally PNG.

00:03:18.575 --> 00:03:21.740
So when you don't need to
get transparent backgrounds,

00:03:21.740 --> 00:03:24.110
you can simply use JPEG.

00:03:24.110 --> 00:03:26.150
But if you need
transparent backgrounds,

00:03:26.150 --> 00:03:28.114
you need to go with PNG.

00:03:28.114 --> 00:03:29.720
But why are we talking about it?

00:03:29.720 --> 00:03:32.255
Does it really matter
which format we use?

00:03:32.255 --> 00:03:33.500
Yes, it does.

00:03:33.500 --> 00:03:34.190
Why?

00:03:34.190 --> 00:03:37.550
Because your file size has
a direct relationship,

00:03:37.550 --> 00:03:39.590
your page load speed,

00:03:39.590 --> 00:03:42.185
and when you have a
low page load speed,

00:03:42.185 --> 00:03:44.600
Google will rank
your website lower.

00:03:44.600 --> 00:03:45.785
It's not what we want.

00:03:45.785 --> 00:03:47.510
So that's why we
need to optimize

00:03:47.510 --> 00:03:49.520
our assets in order to load

00:03:49.520 --> 00:03:52.040
our pages faster and in order to

00:03:52.040 --> 00:03:54.694
improve the usability
of our website.

00:03:54.694 --> 00:03:57.140
So let me show you how you
need to export your images.

00:03:57.140 --> 00:03:59.570
Let's suppose you want
to export discard first,

00:03:59.570 --> 00:04:00.755
you need to select it.

00:04:00.755 --> 00:04:03.530
Then you will head over
to the export section.

00:04:03.530 --> 00:04:06.230
And here you will specify PNG

00:04:06.230 --> 00:04:09.229
because you're going to need
transparent backgrounds.

00:04:09.229 --> 00:04:11.990
Here we can specify whether
we want this element to be

00:04:11.990 --> 00:04:15.335
exported at one x
to x, et cetera.

00:04:15.335 --> 00:04:18.035
What does it mean when
it's set to one x?

00:04:18.035 --> 00:04:20.210
It means you will get
the exact dimension

00:04:20.210 --> 00:04:21.545
that you have here.

00:04:21.545 --> 00:04:23.360
As you can see, its
width is set to

00:04:23.360 --> 00:04:28.655
190 pixels and its height
is set to 216 pixels.

00:04:28.655 --> 00:04:30.859
It's fine. However, nowadays,

00:04:30.859 --> 00:04:33.650
more and more people are
using retina displays.

00:04:33.650 --> 00:04:36.350
Those screens
display twice pixel.

00:04:36.350 --> 00:04:39.590
So instead of exporting
our assets at one x,

00:04:39.590 --> 00:04:41.375
we can set it to two x.

00:04:41.375 --> 00:04:43.685
And now when we exported,

00:04:43.685 --> 00:04:46.055
the width of our file will be

00:04:46.055 --> 00:04:51.410
380 pixels and the height
will be 432 pixels.

00:04:51.410 --> 00:04:53.915
So if a user has a white screen,

00:04:53.915 --> 00:04:55.925
it doesn't lose quality.

00:04:55.925 --> 00:04:58.970
This is the reason that you
should export at two x.

00:04:58.970 --> 00:05:01.130
But if your image
is too big already,

00:05:01.130 --> 00:05:03.740
you don't need to export
it at two x, e.g.

00:05:03.740 --> 00:05:06.485
if the width is set
to 2000 pixels,

00:05:06.485 --> 00:05:08.705
you don't need to
export it at two x.

00:05:08.705 --> 00:05:11.855
And remember when you use an
image element on Webflow,

00:05:11.855 --> 00:05:14.600
Webflow automatically
creates variations

00:05:14.600 --> 00:05:17.344
of your image for
different screen sizes.

00:05:17.344 --> 00:05:20.675
So it basically automatically
optimizes your images.

00:05:20.675 --> 00:05:22.070
But what about other images?

00:05:22.070 --> 00:05:23.240
Let's suppose you want to

00:05:23.240 --> 00:05:25.955
export this project image, okay?

00:05:25.955 --> 00:05:27.185
First you need to select it.

00:05:27.185 --> 00:05:27.650
Again.

00:05:27.650 --> 00:05:29.630
You can export it at two x.

00:05:29.630 --> 00:05:32.810
Or you can change the
image format to JPEG

00:05:32.810 --> 00:05:36.155
since we don't need transparent
background and so on.

00:05:36.155 --> 00:05:38.180
So let me export it at two x.

00:05:38.180 --> 00:05:39.035
There we go.

00:05:39.035 --> 00:05:41.630
Well, most design
software don't let you

